Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST NODE STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The PHP AST uses a uniform four-field shape for every node kind: a
node_type discriminator (one of the PHP_* constants), a value slot
holding the lexeme for leaf nodes (identifiers, literals) or 0 for
interior nodes, a children pointer to a ListCore list of sub-nodes,
and a metadata pointer for kind-specific extra data (visibility flags,
modifiers, etc.). This uniformity lets a single tree walker handle
every PHP construct without per-kind dispatch tables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots laid out in declaration order:
node_type@0, value@8, children@16, metadata@24.
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    children as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PARSER STATE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser state carries everything needed by the recursive-descent
walkers: the token stream produced by the lexer, the running position
within it (incremented by advance/consume), and the pre-computed
length so end-of-stream tests are O(1). Position is tracked by index
rather than by pointer so debug/error messages can report token
numbers without pointer arithmetic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three 8-byte slots: tokens@0 (ListCore handle to the token sequence),
position@8 (0-based index of the next token to consume), length@16
(total token count, fixed at construction).
@End Implementation

Type called "Parser":
    tokens as Integer
    position as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN PARSER ENTRY POINTS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point: takes raw PHP source string, tokenises via the
PHP lexer, constructs a parser, and runs it to completion. No
intermediate persistence - this is the one-shot "give me an AST"
facade that test harnesses and the CLI driver call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls PHPLexer.php_lex(source) to produce a ListCore token sequence.
Calls create_parser(tokens) to wrap it in a Parser state. Tail-calls
parse_program(parser) which walks the entire token stream into a
single PHP_PROGRAM root node. Returns the root AST.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_php_source" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens be proc php_lex from PHPLexer with source
    Let parser be proc create_parser from tokens
    Return proc parse_program from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parser constructor. Initialises position to 0 (first token) and
precomputes length so end-of-stream checks throughout the parser are
constant-time. Using value-of-type with field-as-value initialisation
gives us a flat struct without separate field writes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs a Parser record with tokens=tokens, position=0,
length=ListCore.list_length(tokens). Returns the parser handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes tokens as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be a value of type Parser with
        tokens as tokens,
        position as 0,
        length as proc list_length from ListCore with tokens

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PROGRAM PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry for parsing a PHP file. PHP source starts with an
optional `<?php` opening tag; the lexer emits TOKEN_PHP_OPEN for it
which we silently consume since the AST has no concept of "PHP mode"
vs HTML interleaving (a future bootstrap concern). The loop runs
until end-of-stream collecting every top-level declaration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates the PHP_PROGRAM root node with empty value. If the current
token is TOKEN_PHP_OPEN, advances past it. Loops while not_at_end:
calls parse_declaration and, if non-zero, appends to the program's
children. Returns the program node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let program be proc create_node with PHP_PROGRAM, ""

    Note: Skip PHP opening tag if present
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PHP_OPEN:
        proc advance from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Parse top-level declarations
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let decl be proc parse_declaration from parser
        If decl is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with program, decl
        End If
    End While
    
    Return program
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level declaration dispatcher. PHP permits at file scope:
namespaces, use declarations, classes (with optional abstract/final
modifiers), interfaces, traits, free functions, and free statements.
The dispatch order matters - modifiers (abstract, final) must be
checked BEFORE class so they don't get treated as identifiers; class
itself runs through the same parse_class regardless of which modifier
introduced it because the modifier-collection happens inside that
parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequence of check-and-dispatch tests on the current token:
TOKEN_NAMESPACE -> parse_namespace, TOKEN_USE -> parse_use_declaration,
TOKEN_CLASS / TOKEN_ABSTRACT / TOKEN_FINAL -> parse_class (each path
parses any modifiers internally), TOKEN_INTERFACE -> parse_interface,
TOKEN_TRAIT -> parse_trait, TOKEN_FUNCTION -> parse_function. Falls
through to parse_statement for anything else.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Namespace
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NAMESPACE:
        Return proc parse_namespace from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Use declaration
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_USE:
        Return proc parse_use_declaration from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Class
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CLASS:
        Return proc parse_class from parser
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        Return proc parse_class from parser
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FINAL:
        Return proc parse_class from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Interface
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INTERFACE:
        Return proc parse_interface from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Trait
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_TRAIT:
        Return proc parse_trait from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Function
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Statement
    Return proc parse_statement from parser
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: NAMESPACE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP namespaces have two surface forms: simple `namespace Foo\Bar;`
(applies to entire rest of file) and block `namespace Foo\Bar { ... }`
(applies only within the braces). We distinguish by peeking at what
comes after the qualified name - LEFT_BRACE means block form,
SEMICOLON (or anything else) means simple form. The simple form has
no body; the block form recursively parses declarations until the
matching closing brace.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_NAMESPACE. Parses qualified name (handles `Foo\Bar\Baz`).
Creates PHP_NAMESPACE node with the name as value. If next is
LEFT_BRACE: consumes it, then loops while not_at_end - on
RIGHT_BRACE consumes and returns ns_node; otherwise calls
parse_declaration and appends non-zero results to ns_node.
Otherwise consumes the terminating SEMICOLON. Returns ns_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_namespace" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NAMESPACE
    
    Let name be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
    Let ns_node be proc create_node with PHP_NAMESPACE, name
    
    Note: Check for block syntax or simple syntax
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
        
        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
                proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
                Return ns_node
            End If
            
            Let decl be proc parse_declaration from parser
            If decl is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with ns_node, decl
            End If
        End While
    Otherwise:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    End If
    
    Return ns_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP qualified names use backslash as the namespace separator:
`Foo\Bar\Baz`. A leading backslash denotes fully-qualified (rooted)
names: `\Foo\Bar` means "Foo in the root namespace". We preserve
that prefix in the returned string so resolution code can
distinguish absolute from relative names without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises name="". If current is TOKEN_BACKSLASH, advances and
prepends "\\". Calls expect(TOKEN_IDENTIFIER) for the first segment
and concatenates onto name. Loops while current is TOKEN_BACKSLASH:
advances, concatenates "\\", calls expect(TOKEN_IDENTIFIER) and
concatenates. Returns name.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_qualified_name" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name be ""
    
    Note: Check for leading backslash
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BACKSLASH:
        proc advance from parser
        Set name to "\\"
    End If
    
    Note: Parse name parts
    Let first be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Set name to proc string_concat from StringCore with name, first
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BACKSLASH:
        proc advance from parser
        Set name to proc string_concat from StringCore with name, "\\"
        
        Let part be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        Set name to proc string_concat from StringCore with name, part
    End While
    
    Return name
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: USE DECLARATION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
`use Foo\Bar` and `use Foo\Bar as Baz` are PHP's import mechanism -
they bring a namespaced name into the current scope under either
its own short name or an alias. We preserve the alias in metadata
because the same use-declaration is referenced by every subsequent
unqualified reference to the imported name, and resolution needs
to know whether `Baz` originally was an alias for `Foo\Bar`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_USE. Parses qualified name. Creates
PHP_USE_DECLARATION node with the name as value. If current is
TOKEN_AS, consumes AS, expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the alias,
sets metadata "alias" to the identifier. Consumes terminating
SEMICOLON. Returns use_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_use_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_USE
    
    Let name be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
    Let use_node be proc create_node with PHP_USE_DECLARATION, name
    
    Note: Check for alias
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_AS:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_AS
        Let alias be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        proc set_metadata with use_node, "alias", alias
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return use_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CLASS PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP class declarations have a rich modifier set (abstract, final),
optional `extends Parent`, optional `implements I1, I2, ...`, and a
brace-delimited body of members. Modifiers are collected into a List
so the AST consumer can iterate them uniformly. extends is single
(PHP has single inheritance) but implements is plural - we use
separate metadata keys to preserve that distinction without forcing
the consumer to type-test.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates modifiers List. If current is TOKEN_ABSTRACT, advances and
appends "abstract". If current is TOKEN_FINAL, advances and appends
"final". Consumes TOKEN_CLASS. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the
class name. Creates PHP_CLASS node. Stores modifiers metadata. If
current is TOKEN_EXTENDS, consumes, parses parent qualified name,
sets "extends" metadata. If current is TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS, consumes,
calls parse_interface_list, sets "implements" metadata. Consumes
LEFT_BRACE then loops parsing members via parse_class_member until
RIGHT_BRACE. Appends each non-zero member to the class node.
Returns class_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_class" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse modifiers
    Let modifiers be proc list_create from ListCore
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        proc advance from parser
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "abstract"
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FINAL:
        proc advance from parser
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "final"
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CLASS
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let class_node be proc create_node with PHP_CLASS, name
    
    Note: Store modifiers
    proc set_metadata with class_node, "modifiers", modifiers
    
    Note: Check for extends
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_EXTENDS:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_EXTENDS
        Let parent be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
        proc set_metadata with class_node, "extends", parent
    End If
    
    Note: Check for implements
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS
        Let interfaces be proc parse_interface_list from parser
        proc set_metadata with class_node, "implements", interfaces
    End If
    
    Note: Parse class body
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return class_node
        End If
        
        Let member be proc parse_class_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with class_node, member
        End If
    End While
    
    Return class_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a comma-separated list of interface names following
`implements` or `extends` (for interface-extends-interfaces). At
least one name is required; subsequent names are introduced by
commas. Returns a List rather than a single value because PHP
classes can implement multiple interfaces.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an empty interfaces List. Parses the first qualified name
and appends it. Loops while current is TOKEN_COMMA: advances,
parses next qualified name, appends to interfaces. Returns the
interfaces list.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_interface_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let interfaces be proc list_create from ListCore
    
    Let first be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
    proc list_append from ListCore with interfaces, first
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
        proc advance from parser
        Let name be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
        proc list_append from ListCore with interfaces, name
    End While
    
    Return interfaces
End Process

@Reasoning:
A class body member can be a property, method, or constant - each
introduced by their own keyword - but ANY of them can be preceded by
visibility modifiers (public/protected/private), static, abstract, or
final in any combination (though PHP semantically rejects some
combinations like abstract+final). We collect ALL the modifiers
first, then dispatch on the next token. Visibility defaults to public
when no explicit modifier is given.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises visibility="public". Tests for TOKEN_PUBLIC/PROTECTED/
PRIVATE, advancing past whichever appears and updating visibility.
Initialises is_static, is_abstract, is_final to 0. Tests TOKEN_STATIC/
ABSTRACT/FINAL, advancing past matches and setting the flag. Then
dispatches on the next token: TOKEN_CONST -> parse_class_constant;
TOKEN_FUNCTION -> parse_method (with all collected flags);
TOKEN_VARIABLE -> parse_property (with visibility and is_static).
Returns 0 (failure) if none match.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_class_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse visibility modifiers
    Let visibility be "public"
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC:
        proc advance from parser
        Set visibility to "public"
    Otherwise:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PROTECTED:
            proc advance from parser
            Set visibility to "protected"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PRIVATE:
                proc advance from parser
                Set visibility to "private"
            End If
        End If
    End If
    
    Note: Parse other modifiers
    Let is_static be 0
    Let is_abstract be 0
    Let is_final be 0
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STATIC:
        proc advance from parser
        Set is_static to 1
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        proc advance from parser
        Set is_abstract to 1
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FINAL:
        proc advance from parser
        Set is_final to 1
    End If
    
    Note: Property or method or constant
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONST:
        Return proc parse_class_constant with parser, visibility
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_method with parser, visibility, is_static, is_abstract, is_final
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE:
        Return proc parse_property with parser, visibility, is_static
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP class properties are introduced by a `$variable` token (PHP
variable syntax includes the dollar sign). They can have an optional
default value following `=`. Visibility and is_static come in as
parameters because they were collected by parse_class_member before
dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current token (the variable), extracts its lexeme via
PHPLexer.php_token_value, advances past it. Creates PHP_PROPERTY
node with var_name as value. Sets metadata "visibility" and
"is_static". If current is TOKEN_ASSIGN, advances and calls
parse_expression to read the default value, appending it as a child.
Consumes terminating TOKEN_SEMICOLON. Returns prop_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_property" takes parser as Integer, visibility as Integer, is_static as Integer returns Integer:
    Let var_token be proc current from parser
    Let var_name be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
    proc advance from parser
    
    Let prop_node be proc create_node with PHP_PROPERTY, var_name
    proc set_metadata with prop_node, "visibility", visibility
    proc set_metadata with prop_node, "is_static", is_static
    
    Note: Check for default value
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        proc advance from parser
        Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with prop_node, value
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return prop_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Class constants `const NAME = value;` are accessed via `Class::NAME`.
They REQUIRE a value at declaration (no forward declarations) so the
expression after `=` is non-optional. The visibility parameter
typically defaults to public (older PHP only allowed public consts;
PHP 7.1+ allows visibility modifiers).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_CONST. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the constant name.
Creates PHP_CONSTANT node with the name as value. Sets metadata
"visibility". Consumes TOKEN_ASSIGN. Calls parse_expression for the
value, appends it as a child. Consumes terminating TOKEN_SEMICOLON.
Returns const_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_class_constant" takes parser as Integer, visibility as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONST
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let const_node be proc create_node with PHP_CONSTANT, name
    proc set_metadata with const_node, "visibility", visibility
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN
    
    Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc add_child with const_node, value
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return const_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Class method parsing. Methods share most structure with free functions
(name, parameters, return type, body) but carry additional class-
context flags: visibility, is_static, is_abstract, is_final. Abstract
methods skip the body entirely - they end with a semicolon instead of
a brace block. This shape divergence is checked explicitly because
trying to parse_block on an abstract method would consume the next
real method's body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_FUNCTION. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the method name.
Creates PHP_METHOD node. Sets metadata "visibility", "is_static",
"is_abstract", "is_final". Consumes LEFT_PAREN, calls
parse_parameter_list, stores "parameters" metadata, consumes
RIGHT_PAREN. If next is TOKEN_COLON, advances and parses return type,
stores "return_type" metadata. If is_abstract == 1, consumes
SEMICOLON and skips the body. Otherwise parses block via parse_block
and appends as a child. Returns method_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_method" takes parser as Integer, visibility as Integer, is_static as Integer, is_abstract as Integer, is_final as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let method_node be proc create_node with PHP_METHOD, name
    
    proc set_metadata with method_node, "visibility", visibility
    proc set_metadata with method_node, "is_static", is_static
    proc set_metadata with method_node, "is_abstract", is_abstract
    proc set_metadata with method_node, "is_final", is_final
    
    Note: Parse parameters
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let params be proc parse_parameter_list from parser
    proc set_metadata with method_node, "parameters", params
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Note: Parse return type
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance from parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type from parser
        proc set_metadata with method_node, "return_type", return_type
    End If
    
    Note: Abstract methods have no body
    If is_abstract is equal to 1:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Otherwise:
        Note: Parse body
        Let body be proc parse_block from parser
        proc add_child with method_node, body
    End If
    
    Return method_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: INTERFACE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP interfaces declare type signatures without implementations. They
support multiple inheritance (an interface can extend multiple
interfaces - unlike classes), so the extends clause uses
parse_interface_list to collect the comma-separated parents.
Interface members are restricted to method signatures and constants;
parse_interface_member enforces that.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_INTERFACE. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the interface
name. Creates PHP_INTERFACE node. If next is TOKEN_EXTENDS, consumes
and calls parse_interface_list, stores "extends" metadata. Consumes
LEFT_BRACE then loops members via parse_interface_member, appending
non-zero results to the interface node until RIGHT_BRACE. Returns
interface_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_interface" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INTERFACE
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let interface_node be proc create_node with PHP_INTERFACE, name
    
    Note: Check for extends
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_EXTENDS:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_EXTENDS
        Let parents be proc parse_interface_list from parser
        proc set_metadata with interface_node, "extends", parents
    End If
    
    Note: Parse interface body
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return interface_node
        End If
        
        Let member be proc parse_interface_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with interface_node, member
        End If
    End While
    
    Return interface_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Interface members are EITHER method signatures (no body, just the
shape) OR constants. Methods are implicitly public AND abstract (no
modifier needed; redundant `public` is allowed and silently consumed
because legacy PHP code commonly writes it). Properties are NOT
allowed in interfaces - if encountered, we return 0 letting the
caller produce an error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If current is TOKEN_PUBLIC, advances past it (silently consumed -
redundant in interfaces). If next is TOKEN_FUNCTION: consumes,
expects identifier name, creates PHP_METHOD with metadata
visibility="public" is_abstract=1; parses parameter list, stores
"parameters" metadata; optionally parses return type; consumes
terminating SEMICOLON. If TOKEN_CONST, dispatches to
parse_class_constant with visibility="public". Otherwise returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_interface_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Interface methods are always public and abstract
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC:
        proc advance from parser
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION
        
        Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        Let method_node be proc create_node with PHP_METHOD, name
        proc set_metadata with method_node, "visibility", "public"
        proc set_metadata with method_node, "is_abstract", 1
        
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
        Let params be proc parse_parameter_list from parser
        proc set_metadata with method_node, "parameters", params
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
            proc advance from parser
            Let return_type be proc parse_type from parser
            proc set_metadata with method_node, "return_type", return_type
        End If
        
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return method_node
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONST:
        Return proc parse_class_constant with parser, "public"
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TRAIT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
PHP traits are reusable method/property fragments that classes can
"use" via `use TraitName`. Structurally they parse exactly like
classes (properties, methods, constants) but they're not
instantiable on their own and can't extend or implement. We reuse
parse_class_member for body parsing because the member shapes are
identical.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_TRAIT. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the trait name.
Creates PHP_TRAIT node. Consumes LEFT_BRACE. Loops parsing members
via parse_class_member until RIGHT_BRACE, appending non-zero results
to the trait node. Returns trait_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_trait" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_TRAIT
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let trait_node be proc create_node with PHP_TRAIT, name
    
    Note: Parse trait body
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return trait_node
        End If
        
        Let member be proc parse_class_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with trait_node, member
        End If
    End While
    
    Return trait_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FUNCTION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level (free) PHP function. No visibility or modifiers because
free functions can't be abstract or have visibility. Otherwise
identical shape to a method: name, parameter list, optional return
type, body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_FUNCTION. Expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for the name.
Creates PHP_FUNCTION node. Consumes LEFT_PAREN, calls
parse_parameter_list, stores "parameters" metadata, consumes
RIGHT_PAREN. If next is TOKEN_COLON, advances and parses return
type, stores "return_type". Parses block via parse_block and
appends as a child. Returns func_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION
    
    Let name be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let func_node be proc create_node with PHP_FUNCTION, name
    
    Note: Parse parameters
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let params be proc parse_parameter_list from parser
    proc set_metadata with func_node, "parameters", params
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Note: Parse return type
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance from parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type from parser
        proc set_metadata with func_node, "return_type", return_type
    End If
    
    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with func_node, body
    
    Return func_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parameter lists are comma-separated and CAN be empty (just `()`).
The empty-paren short-circuit at the top is what permits zero-arg
functions without trying to parse a missing first parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates empty params List. If current is TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, returns
the empty list immediately. Otherwise parses the first parameter via
parse_parameter and appends. Loops while current is TOKEN_COMMA:
advances, parses next parameter, appends. Returns params.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_parameter_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let params be proc list_create from ListCore

    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        Return params
    End If

    Note: Parse first parameter
    Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
    proc list_append from ListCore with params, param
    
    Note: Parse remaining parameters
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
        proc advance from parser
        Let p be proc parse_parameter from parser
        proc list_append from ListCore with params, p
    End While
    
    Return params
End Process

@Reasoning:
A PHP parameter has up to four pieces in order: optional type hint
(`int`, `?MyClass`, etc.), optional by-reference marker (`&`), the
variable name (`$foo`), and an optional default value (`= expr`). We
test each section in turn and store its presence in metadata. The
type hint test uses is_type_keyword to handle both built-in types and
qualified names.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates PHP_PARAMETER node. If is_type_keyword returns 1, calls
parse_type and stores "type" metadata. If current is
TOKEN_BITWISE_AND, advances and sets "by_reference" metadata to 1.
Reads variable name from current token via php_token_value, consumes
TOKEN_VARIABLE, stores "name" metadata. If current is TOKEN_ASSIGN,
advances and calls parse_expression for the default, appending as a
child. Returns param_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let param_node be proc create_node with PHP_PARAMETER, ""
    
    Note: Parse type hint
    If proc is_type_keyword from parser:
        Let type_hint be proc parse_type from parser
        proc set_metadata with param_node, "type", type_hint
    End If
    
    Note: Parse by-reference
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BITWISE_AND:
        proc advance from parser
        proc set_metadata with param_node, "by_reference", 1
    End If
    
    Note: Parse variable name
    Let var_token be proc current from parser
    Let var_name be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
    proc set_metadata with param_node, "name", var_name
    
    Note: Parse default value
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        proc advance from parser
        Let default_val be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with param_node, default_val
    End If
    
    Return param_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP type hints accept an optional `?` nullable prefix plus one of:
a built-in type keyword (int/float/string/bool/array/callable/void/
mixed/object/iterable) or a class qualified name (`Foo\Bar`). The
nullable prefix is recorded by prepending `?` to the returned type
name so callers can detect nullable-ness with a single string check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises is_nullable=0. If current is TOKEN_QUESTION, advances and
sets is_nullable=1. Cascading If-tests for each built-in type token
(TOKEN_INT/FLOAT/STRING_TYPE/BOOL/ARRAY/CALLABLE/VOID/MIXED/OBJECT/
ITERABLE), each advancing and setting type_name to the canonical
lowercase name. If none match, calls parse_qualified_name as the
fallback (class names). If is_nullable == 1, prepends "?" to
type_name. Returns type_name.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check for nullable type (?)
    Let is_nullable be 0
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
        proc advance from parser
        Set is_nullable to 1
    End If
    
    Note: Parse type name
    Let type_name be ""
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INT:
        proc advance from parser
        Set type_name to "int"
    Otherwise:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FLOAT:
            proc advance from parser
            Set type_name to "float"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STRING_TYPE:
                proc advance from parser
                Set type_name to "string"
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BOOL:
                    proc advance from parser
                    Set type_name to "bool"
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ARRAY:
                        proc advance from parser
                        Set type_name to "array"
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CALLABLE:
                            proc advance from parser
                            Set type_name to "callable"
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VOID:
                                proc advance from parser
                                Set type_name to "void"
                            Otherwise:
                                If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_MIXED:
                                    proc advance from parser
                                    Set type_name to "mixed"
                                Otherwise:
                                    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_OBJECT:
                                        proc advance from parser
                                        Set type_name to "object"
                                    Otherwise:
                                        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ITERABLE:
                                            proc advance from parser
                                            Set type_name to "iterable"
                                        Otherwise:
                                            Note: Class name
                                            Set type_name to proc parse_qualified_name from parser
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    
    If is_nullable is equal to 1:
        Set type_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with "?", type_name
    End If
    
    Return type_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate that returns 1 if the current token could legitimately
start a type hint. Used by parse_parameter to decide whether to
attempt parse_type before reading the variable name. We include
TOKEN_QUESTION (nullable prefix) and TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (class names)
in addition to the built-in type keywords.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequence of If-checks against each token type that's valid as the
start of a type hint: TOKEN_INT/FLOAT/STRING_TYPE/BOOL/ARRAY/CALLABLE/
VOID/MIXED/OBJECT/ITERABLE/IDENTIFIER/QUESTION. Returns 1 on first
match. Returns 0 after all tests fail.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_type_keyword" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FLOAT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STRING_TYPE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BOOL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ARRAY:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CALLABLE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VOID:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_MIXED:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_OBJECT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ITERABLE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATEMENT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement dispatcher. PHP has a rich statement vocabulary - control
flow (if/while/do-while/for/foreach/switch), flow modifiers (return/
break/continue), exception handling (try/throw), I/O (echo), scope
modifiers (global/static), and bare expression statements as the
fallback. Order matters where prefix tokens overlap (e.g., `static`
can introduce a static-variable statement OR be a method modifier;
in statement context it's the former).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Long sequence of check-and-dispatch tests on the current token,
each tail-calling its dedicated parser: LEFT_BRACE -> parse_block,
IF -> parse_if_statement, WHILE -> parse_while_statement, DO ->
parse_do_while_statement, FOR -> parse_for_statement, FOREACH ->
parse_foreach_statement, SWITCH -> parse_switch_statement, RETURN ->
parse_return_statement, BREAK/CONTINUE -> advance, consume SEMICOLON,
create PHP_BREAK_STMT/PHP_CONTINUE_STMT, TRY -> parse_try_statement,
THROW -> parse_throw_statement, ECHO -> parse_echo_statement, GLOBAL
-> parse_global_statement, STATIC -> parse_static_statement.
Fallthrough: parses expression, consumes SEMICOLON, wraps in
PHP_EXPRESSION_STMT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Block
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE:
        Return proc parse_block from parser
    End If
    
    Note: If statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Return proc parse_if_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: While loop
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_WHILE:
        Return proc parse_while_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Do-while loop
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DO:
        Return proc parse_do_while_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: For loop
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        Return proc parse_for_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Foreach loop
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FOREACH:
        Return proc parse_foreach_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Switch statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SWITCH:
        Return proc parse_switch_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Return statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RETURN:
        Return proc parse_return_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Break statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BREAK:
        proc advance from parser
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return proc create_node with PHP_BREAK_STMT, ""
    End If
    
    Note: Continue statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONTINUE:
        proc advance from parser
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return proc create_node with PHP_CONTINUE_STMT, ""
    End If
    
    Note: Try-catch statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_TRY:
        Return proc parse_try_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Throw statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_THROW:
        Return proc parse_throw_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Echo statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ECHO:
        Return proc parse_echo_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Global statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_GLOBAL:
        Return proc parse_global_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Static statement
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STATIC:
        Return proc parse_static_statement from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Expression statement
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    
    Let stmt be proc create_node with PHP_EXPRESSION_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with stmt, expr
    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
Brace-delimited statement block. Used by function/method bodies and
nested compound statements (`if (...) { ... }`). Statements are
parsed recursively, allowing blocks to nest arbitrarily.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes LEFT_BRACE. Creates PHP_BLOCK_STMT node. Loops while
not_at_end: if RIGHT_BRACE consumes it and returns block. Otherwise
calls parse_statement and appends non-zero results to the block.
Returns block.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
    
    Let block be proc create_node with PHP_BLOCK_STMT, ""
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return block
        End If
        
        Let stmt be proc parse_statement from parser
        If stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with block, stmt
        End If
    End While
    
    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP if/elseif/else chains parse with right-recursion: an `elseif`
branch recursively parses as another if-statement, naturally building
a nested-if tree. This is the cleanest way to capture
arbitrarily-long `if elseif elseif elseif else` chains without a
sentinel-loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_IF and LEFT_PAREN. Parses condition expression.
Consumes RIGHT_PAREN. Parses then_branch via parse_statement. Creates
PHP_IF_STMT node and appends condition then then_branch as children.
If current is TOKEN_ELSEIF, recursively calls parse_if_statement and
appends the result. Otherwise if TOKEN_ELSE, advances and parses
else_branch via parse_statement, appends. Returns if_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IF
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Let then_branch be proc parse_statement from parser
    
    Let if_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_IF_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with if_stmt, condition
    proc add_child with if_stmt, then_branch
    
    Note: Check for else or elseif
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ELSEIF:
        Let elseif_branch be proc parse_if_statement from parser
        proc add_child with if_stmt, elseif_branch
    Otherwise:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
            proc advance from parser
            Let else_branch be proc parse_statement from parser
            proc add_child with if_stmt, else_branch
        End If
    End If
    
    Return if_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`while (cond) body` - pre-test loop. Children stored in [condition,
body] order matching execution order so the AST consumer doesn't have
to remember reversed positions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes WHILE, LEFT_PAREN, parses condition expression, consumes
RIGHT_PAREN. Parses body via parse_statement. Creates PHP_WHILE_STMT,
appends condition then body. Returns while_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_WHILE
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser
    
    Let while_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_WHILE_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with while_stmt, condition
    proc add_child with while_stmt, body
    
    Return while_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`do body while (cond);` - post-test loop guaranteeing at least one
body execution. The terminating semicolon (uncommon for control
structures) is mandatory in PHP and must be consumed explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes DO. Parses body via parse_statement. Consumes WHILE,
LEFT_PAREN. Parses condition. Consumes RIGHT_PAREN, SEMICOLON.
Creates PHP_DO_WHILE_STMT, appends body then condition (matching
source order). Returns do_while_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_do_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DO
    
    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_WHILE
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    
    Let do_while_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_DO_WHILE_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with do_while_stmt, body
    proc add_child with do_while_stmt, condition
    
    Return do_while_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
C-style `for (init; cond; update) body`. Each of init/cond/update is
optional (`for (;;)` is the infinite-loop idiom). We use 0 sentinels
to represent missing clauses and only append non-zero ones to the
AST, so the consumer can detect missing pieces by counting children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes FOR, LEFT_PAREN. Initialises init=0; if next isn't SEMICOLON,
parses init expression. Consumes SEMICOLON. Same pattern for
condition then SEMICOLON, then update then RIGHT_PAREN. Parses body
via parse_statement. Creates PHP_FOR_STMT; appends init, condition,
update each only if non-zero, then appends body unconditionally.
Returns for_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FOR
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    
    Note: Init
    Let init be 0
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        Set init to proc parse_expression from parser
    End If
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    
    Note: Condition
    Let condition be 0
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        Set condition to proc parse_expression from parser
    End If
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    
    Note: Update
    Let update be 0
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        Set update to proc parse_expression from parser
    End If
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser
    
    Let for_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_FOR_STMT, ""
    If init is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, init
    End If
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, condition
    End If
    If update is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, update
    End If
    proc add_child with for_stmt, body
    
    Return for_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP foreach has two syntactic shapes: value-only (`foreach ($arr as
$value)`) and key-value (`foreach ($arr as $key => $value)`). We
parse the first expression after `as`, then peek for `=>` to
disambiguate: if present the first expression was the key, otherwise
it was the value. has_key is recorded so the consumer can iterate
the right shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes FOREACH, LEFT_PAREN. Parses iterable expression. Consumes
TOKEN_AS. Parses first expression. If current is TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW,
advances, sets has_key=1, sets key=first, parses value expression.
Otherwise sets value=first. Consumes RIGHT_PAREN. Parses body.
Creates PHP_FOREACH_STMT, appends iterable, optionally key, value,
body. Returns foreach_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_foreach_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FOREACH
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    
    Let iterable be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_AS
    
    Note: Check for key => value syntax
    Let has_key be 0
    Let key be 0
    Let value be 0
    
    Let first be proc parse_expression from parser
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW:
        proc advance from parser
        Set has_key to 1
        Set key to first
        Set value to proc parse_expression from parser
    Otherwise:
        Set value to first
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser
    
    Let foreach_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_FOREACH_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with foreach_stmt, iterable
    If has_key is equal to 1:
        proc add_child with foreach_stmt, key
    End If
    proc add_child with foreach_stmt, value
    proc add_child with foreach_stmt, body
    
    Return foreach_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP switch with case and default clauses. The discriminant expression
becomes the FIRST child; all case/default clauses follow in source
order. Like JavaScript, PHP switch has fall-through unless `break`
appears - we preserve clause boundaries faithfully so the consumer
can detect missing breaks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes SWITCH, LEFT_PAREN, parses discriminant expression, consumes
RIGHT_PAREN, LEFT_BRACE. Creates PHP_SWITCH_STMT and appends
discriminant as first child. Loops while not_at_end: RIGHT_BRACE
consumes and returns; TOKEN_CASE -> parse_case_clause and append;
TOKEN_DEFAULT -> parse_default_clause and append. Returns
switch_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_switch_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SWITCH
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE
    
    Let switch_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_SWITCH_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with switch_stmt, expr
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return switch_stmt
        End If
        
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CASE:
            Let case_clause be proc parse_case_clause from parser
            proc add_child with switch_stmt, case_clause
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DEFAULT:
                Let default_clause be proc parse_default_clause from parser
                proc add_child with switch_stmt, default_clause
            End If
        End If
    End While
    
    Return switch_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
A `case <value>: stmts` clause. PHP's fall-through means stmts are
parsed until we see the next case/default/closing-brace - those
boundary tokens tell us to stop. The value expression is appended as
the first child; subsequent children are statements.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes CASE. Parses value expression. Consumes COLON. Creates
PHP_CASE_CLAUSE node and appends value. Loops while not_at_end: on
CASE/DEFAULT/RIGHT_BRACE returns case_node. Otherwise parses a
statement via parse_statement and appends. Returns case_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_case_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CASE
    Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON
    
    Let case_node be proc create_node with PHP_CASE_CLAUSE, ""
    proc add_child with case_node, value
    
    Note: Parse statements until next case or default
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CASE:
            Return case_node
        End If
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DEFAULT:
            Return case_node
        End If
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            Return case_node
        End If
        
        Let stmt be proc parse_statement from parser
        proc add_child with case_node, stmt
    End While
    
    Return case_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Default clause within switch. Has no value expression - the literal
string "default" goes into the node's value slot to distinguish it
from regular case clauses without needing a new node-type constant.
Otherwise identical statement-collection logic to parse_case_clause.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes DEFAULT, COLON. Creates PHP_CASE_CLAUSE with value="default".
Loops while not_at_end: on CASE/DEFAULT/RIGHT_BRACE returns;
otherwise parses statement and appends. Returns case_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_default_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DEFAULT
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON
    
    Let case_node be proc create_node with PHP_CASE_CLAUSE, "default"
    
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CASE:
            Return case_node
        End If
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DEFAULT:
            Return case_node
        End If
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            Return case_node
        End If
        
        Let stmt be proc parse_statement from parser
        proc add_child with case_node, stmt
    End While
    
    Return case_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`return;` (void return) and `return expr;` (with value). We test for
immediate SEMICOLON to decide whether to parse an expression. The
optional-child shape means the consumer can detect void return via
empty children list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes RETURN. Creates PHP_RETURN_STMT. If next is NOT SEMICOLON,
parses expression and appends. Consumes SEMICOLON. Returns return_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_return_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RETURN
    
    Let return_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_RETURN_STMT, ""
    
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with return_stmt, expr
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return return_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP try/catch/finally with multiple catch clauses supported. The body
is required (always first child); zero-or-more catch clauses follow;
an optional finally comes last. Empty children after the body indicate
a bare try (which PHP requires to have AT LEAST one catch or finally;
the parser is liberal here, validation belongs in semantic analysis).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TRY. Parses body via parse_block. Creates PHP_TRY_STMT and
appends body. Loops while next is TOKEN_CATCH: calls
parse_catch_clause and appends. If next is TOKEN_FINALLY: calls
parse_finally_clause and appends. Returns try_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_try_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_TRY
    
    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    
    Let try_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_TRY_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with try_stmt, body
    
    Note: Parse catch clauses
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CATCH:
        Let catch_clause be proc parse_catch_clause from parser
        proc add_child with try_stmt, catch_clause
    End While
    
    Note: Parse finally clause
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FINALLY:
        Let finally_clause be proc parse_finally_clause from parser
        proc add_child with try_stmt, finally_clause
    End If
    
    Return try_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`catch (ExceptionType $var) { body }`. The exception type is a
qualified name (can be `\Namespace\ClassName`). The bound variable is
OPTIONAL in PHP 8+ (`catch (Exception)` is valid) - we permit empty
var_name. Both type and variable are stored in metadata, the body is
the only child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes CATCH, LEFT_PAREN. Parses exception_type via
parse_qualified_name. Initialises var_name="". If next is
TOKEN_VARIABLE, reads its name via php_token_value, advances. Consumes
RIGHT_PAREN. Parses body via parse_block. Creates PHP_CATCH_CLAUSE,
sets metadata "exception_type" and "variable". Appends body. Returns
catch_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_catch_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CATCH
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    
    Let exception_type be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
    
    Let var_name be ""
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE:
        Let var_token be proc current from parser
        Set var_name to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
        proc advance from parser
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    
    Let catch_node be proc create_node with PHP_CATCH_CLAUSE, ""
    proc set_metadata with catch_node, "exception_type", exception_type
    proc set_metadata with catch_node, "variable", var_name
    proc add_child with catch_node, body
    
    Return catch_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`finally { body }`. Always runs after try and any matching catch.
No type or variable - just a body block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes FINALLY. Parses body via parse_block. Creates
PHP_FINALLY_CLAUSE, appends body. Returns finally_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_finally_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FINALLY
    
    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    
    Let finally_node be proc create_node with PHP_FINALLY_CLAUSE, ""
    proc add_child with finally_node, body
    
    Return finally_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`throw expr;` - the expression must evaluate to an instance of
Throwable (a runtime check, not a parse-time one). PHP 8 made throw
an EXPRESSION too (usable in ternary, etc.) but we keep it as a
statement here because the bootstrap parser doesn't yet handle the
expression form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes THROW. Parses expression. Consumes SEMICOLON. Creates
PHP_THROW_STMT and appends expression. Returns throw_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_throw_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_THROW
    
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    
    Let throw_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_THROW_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with throw_stmt, expr
    
    Return throw_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`echo expr1, expr2, ...;` outputs one or more expressions
concatenated. PHP also has `print` (function-like, returns 1) but
they're parsed via expression statement, not here. Each expression
becomes a child of the echo node; the consumer concatenates them at
emit time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes ECHO. Creates PHP_ECHO_STMT. Parses first expression and
appends. Loops while current is TOKEN_COMMA: advances, parses next
expression, appends. Consumes SEMICOLON. Returns echo_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_echo_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ECHO
    
    Let echo_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_ECHO_STMT, ""
    
    Note: Parse comma-separated expressions
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc add_child with echo_stmt, expr
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
        proc advance from parser
        Let e be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with echo_stmt, e
    End While
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return echo_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`global $a, $b, $c;` imports global-scope variables into function-
local scope. PHP scoping defaults are function-local; without an
explicit global declaration, accessing `$a` inside a function gets a
new local. Each declared variable becomes a child of the global
node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes GLOBAL. Creates PHP_GLOBAL_STMT. Reads first variable token,
extracts name via php_token_value, consumes TOKEN_VARIABLE. Creates a
PHP_VARIABLE node and appends to global_stmt. Loops while current is
TOKEN_COMMA: advances, reads next variable, creates PHP_VARIABLE
node, appends. Consumes SEMICOLON. Returns global_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_global_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_GLOBAL
    
    Let global_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_GLOBAL_STMT, ""
    
    Let var_token be proc current from parser
    Let var_name be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
    
    Let var_node be proc create_node with PHP_VARIABLE, var_name
    proc add_child with global_stmt, var_node
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
        proc advance from parser
        Let vt be proc current from parser
        Let vn be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with vt
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
        
        Let v be proc create_node with PHP_VARIABLE, vn
        proc add_child with global_stmt, v
    End While
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return global_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
`static $var = init;` declares a function-local variable that
PERSISTS across calls (initialised once, on first entry). Bootstrap
parser handles single-variable form only; PHP also permits
comma-separated forms which higher versions will extend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes STATIC. Creates PHP_STATIC_STMT. Reads variable token,
extracts name, consumes TOKEN_VARIABLE. Creates PHP_VARIABLE node. If
next is TOKEN_ASSIGN, advances and parses initial value, appending to
the variable node. Appends the variable node to static_stmt.
Consumes SEMICOLON. Returns static_stmt.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_static_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STATIC
    
    Let static_stmt be proc create_node with PHP_STATIC_STMT, ""
    
    Let var_token be proc current from parser
    Let var_name be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
    
    Let var_node be proc create_node with PHP_VARIABLE, var_name
    
    Note: Check for initialization
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        proc advance from parser
        Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with var_node, value
    End If
    
    proc add_child with static_stmt, var_node
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return static_stmt
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point for expression parsing. Delegates to parse_ternary, which
is the lowest-precedence operator in PHP. Each precedence level is a
separate function and they cascade in precedence order (lowest at
top); standard recursive-descent shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tail-calls parse_ternary(parser) and returns its result.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc parse_ternary from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP's `cond ? then : else` ternary expression. Right-associative
(parses recursively into parse_expression for both branches) so
chained `a ? b : c ? d : e` parses as `a ? b : (c ? d : e)`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left-hand expression via parse_logical_or. If next is
TOKEN_QUESTION: advances, parses then_expr via recursive
parse_expression, consumes COLON, parses else_expr via recursive
parse_expression. Creates PHP_TERNARY_EXPR with value="?:", appends
condition, then_expr, else_expr. Returns the ternary. Otherwise
returns the left expression unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_ternary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_logical_or from parser
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
        proc advance from parser
        Let then_expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON
        Let else_expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        
        Let ternary be proc create_node with PHP_TERNARY_EXPR, "?:"
        proc add_child with ternary, expr
        proc add_child with ternary, then_expr
        proc add_child with ternary, else_expr
        Return ternary
    End If
    
    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP has TWO short-circuit OR operators with DIFFERENT precedence: `||`
(high precedence, same level as `&&`) and `or` (very low precedence,
below assignment). Most languages have just one - PHP keeps both for
shell-script-style idioms. We handle both here but with subtle
precedence ordering: `||` is left-associative within the while loop;
`or` is checked AFTER the while loop terminates so it binds looser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_logical_and. Loop while current is
TOKEN_LOGICAL_OR (`||`): reads operator lexeme, advances, parses
right via parse_logical_and, creates PHP_BINARY_EXPR with the
operator, appends left and right; sets left = new binary (left-
associative). After the loop, if current is TOKEN_OR (`or`): same
shape but only once because `or` binds the loosest. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_logical_or" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_logical_and from parser
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_OR:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_logical_and from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_OR:
        Set op_token to proc current from parser
        Set op to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Set right to proc parse_logical_and from parser
        
        Set binary to proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Return binary
    End If
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP's `&&` (high precedence) and `and` (very low precedence) - same
duality as ||/or, kept for the same legacy-script reasons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_equality. Loops while TOKEN_LOGICAL_AND
collecting binary nodes left-associatively. After the loop, single
test for TOKEN_AND (`and`) which produces one binary if present.
Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_logical_and" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_equality from parser
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_AND:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_equality from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_AND:
        Set op_token to proc current from parser
        Set op to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Set right to proc parse_equality from parser
        
        Set binary to proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Return binary
    End If
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Equality operators: `==`, `!=`, `===` (identical, no type coercion),
`!==` (not identical). PHP's loose `==` is famously footgun-prone -
we just preserve the operator lexeme in the binary node; downstream
type-checking warns about loose comparisons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_comparison. Loops while match_any returns one
of TOKEN_EQUAL/NOT_EQUAL/IDENTICAL/NOT_IDENTICAL (match_any
auto-advances on match): reads the matched operator via previous,
parses right via parse_comparison, creates PHP_BINARY_EXPR with that
operator, appends left and right, sets left=binary. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_equality" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_comparison from parser
    
    While proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTICAL, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NOT_IDENTICAL:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_comparison from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comparison operators: `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`, and PHP's spaceship `<=>`
(returns -1/0/1 like Perl/C++). The spaceship is sort-friendly and
fits the same precedence level.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_bitwise_or. Loops while match_any returns one
of LESS_THAN/LESS_EQUAL/GREATER_THAN/GREATER_EQUAL/SPACESHIP. Builds
left-associative PHP_BINARY_EXPR chain. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comparison" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_or from parser
    
    While proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LESS_THAN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, PHPLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_THAN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SPACESHIP:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_bitwise_or from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise OR (`|`). Just below XOR in precedence. Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_bitwise_xor. Loops while current is
TOKEN_BITWISE_OR: reads operator, advances, parses right via
parse_bitwise_xor, builds PHP_BINARY_EXPR with the operator
left-associatively. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_or" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_xor from parser
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BITWISE_OR:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_bitwise_xor from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise XOR (`^`). Below OR (in PHP precedence terms higher than OR
but the implementation cascades downward into AND). Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_bitwise_and. Loops while current is
TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR: same pattern as bitwise_or - operator, advance,
right, binary, left=binary. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_xor" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_and from parser
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_bitwise_and from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise AND (`&`). The same token is reused at parameter position for
by-reference (`function f(&$x)`) - the parser context determines which.
Here in expression context it's always bitwise AND.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_shift. Loops while current is TOKEN_BITWISE_AND:
operator, advance, right, build binary left-associatively. Returns
left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_and" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_shift from parser
    
    While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BITWISE_AND:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_shift from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bit-shift operators (`<<` left-shift, `>>` arithmetic right-shift).
No unsigned-shift in PHP (unlike Java's `>>>`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_addition. Loops while match_any returns one of
TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT or TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT (auto-advancing): reads operator
via previous, parses right via parse_addition, builds binary
left-associatively. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_shift" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_addition from parser
    
    While proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_addition from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Additive operators: `+`, `-`, AND PHP's string-concat `.` - they share
the same precedence level in PHP (unusual; many languages give concat
its own level). All three are handled in one loop with match_any.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_multiplication. Loops while match_any returns
PLUS, MINUS, or CONCAT (`.`). Reads operator via previous, parses
right via parse_multiplication, builds binary left-associatively.
Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_addition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_multiplication from parser
    
    While proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PLUS, PHPLexer.TOKEN_MINUS, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONCAT:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_multiplication from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiplicative operators: `*`, `/`, `%`. Higher precedence than
addition. PHP's `/` always produces float (no separate int division
operator).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_power. Loops while match_any returns STAR,
SLASH, or PERCENT. Reads operator, parses right via parse_power,
builds binary left-associatively. Returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_multiplication" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_power from parser
    
    While proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STAR, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SLASH, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_power from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Set left to binary
    End While
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Power operator `**`. RIGHT-associative (unlike most binary ops) so
`2 ** 3 ** 2` = `2 ** 9` = 512, not `8 ** 2` = 64. This matches
mathematical convention. Implementation: recurse into parse_power
(not parse_instanceof) for the right operand.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_instanceof. If current is TOKEN_POWER (only
once, not looped, because right-associativity): reads operator,
advances, recursively calls parse_power for the right operand, builds
binary, returns it. Otherwise returns left unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_power" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_instanceof from parser
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_POWER:
        Let op_token be proc current from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let right be proc parse_power from parser
        
        Let binary be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with binary, left
        proc add_child with binary, right
        Return binary
    End If
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
`$obj instanceof ClassName` tests whether the object is of (or
inherits from) the given class. The right side MUST be a class name -
not an arbitrary expression - so we use parse_qualified_name and put
the result in the node's value slot rather than as a child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses left via parse_unary. If current is TOKEN_INSTANCEOF: advances,
parses type_name via parse_qualified_name, creates
PHP_INSTANCEOF_EXPR with type_name as value, appends left as the
sole child. Otherwise returns left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_instanceof" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_unary from parser
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INSTANCEOF:
        proc advance from parser
        
        Let type_name be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
        
        Let instanceof be proc create_node with PHP_INSTANCEOF_EXPR, type_name
        proc add_child with instanceof, left
        Return instanceof
    End If
    
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary prefix operators: `!`, `~`, `+`, `-`, `++`, `--`, and `clone`.
Most produce a PHP_UNARY_EXPR with prefix=1 in metadata; clone is
distinct (PHP_CLONE_EXPR) because it has its own runtime semantics.
We recursively call parse_unary for the operand to support chained
prefix operators like `!!$x`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If match_any returns one of LOGICAL_NOT/BITWISE_NOT/PLUS/MINUS/
INCREMENT/DECREMENT: reads operator via previous, recursively calls
parse_unary for operand, creates PHP_UNARY_EXPR with operator,
sets metadata "prefix"=1, appends operand, returns. If current is
TOKEN_CLONE: advances, parses operand via recursive parse_unary,
creates PHP_CLONE_EXPR, appends operand, returns. Fallthrough:
tail-calls parse_postfix(parser).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_unary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Prefix operators
    If proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_NOT, PHPLexer.TOKEN_BITWISE_NOT, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PLUS, PHPLexer.TOKEN_MINUS, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let operand be proc parse_unary from parser
        
        Let unary be proc create_node with PHP_UNARY_EXPR, op
        proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", 1
        proc add_child with unary, operand
        Return unary
    End If
    
    Note: Clone
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CLONE:
        proc advance from parser
        Set operand to proc parse_unary from parser
        
        Let clone_expr be proc create_node with PHP_CLONE_EXPR, ""
        proc add_child with clone_expr, operand
        Return clone_expr
    End If
    
    Note: Postfix and primary
    Return proc parse_postfix from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Postfix-and-chained-access handler. After a primary expression we
may chain any number of postfix operators (++/--), function calls
(`(args)`), member accesses (`->member`), static accesses
(`::member`), or array indexing (`[index]`). This is the looping
core of PHP's "expression suffix" grammar. After the loop, we ALSO
handle assignment operators (`=`, `+=`, etc.) at this level because
assignment in PHP has lower precedence than most things but binds
tighter than the comma operator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses expr via parse_primary. Loop with done flag: INCREMENT/
DECREMENT advance and wrap expr in PHP_UNARY_EXPR with metadata
"prefix"=0; LEFT_PAREN dispatches to parse_call(parser, expr); ARROW
(`->`) advances, expects identifier, creates PHP_MEMBER_EXPR with
member name, appends expr, replaces expr; DOUBLE_COLON (`::`) same
shape but PHP_STATIC_MEMBER_EXPR; LEFT_BRACKET advances, parses index,
consumes RIGHT_BRACKET, creates PHP_INDEX_EXPR appending expr+index.
Anything else sets done=1. After loop, if match_any returns one of
ASSIGN/PLUS_ASSIGN/MINUS_ASSIGN/STAR_ASSIGN/SLASH_ASSIGN/PERCENT_ASSIGN/
CONCAT_ASSIGN: reads operator via previous, parses right via
parse_expression (full precedence, so RHS can be a ternary etc.),
creates PHP_ASSIGN_EXPR with operator. Returns expr or assign.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_postfix" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_primary from parser
    
    Note: Postfix operators and member access
    Let done be 0
    While done is equal to 0:
        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT:
            proc advance from parser
            Let unary be proc create_node with PHP_UNARY_EXPR, "++"
            proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", 0
            proc add_child with unary, expr
            Set expr to unary
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT:
                proc advance from parser
                Set unary to proc create_node with PHP_UNARY_EXPR, "--"
                proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", 0
                proc add_child with unary, expr
                Set expr to unary
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
                    Note: Function call
                    Set expr to proc parse_call with parser, expr
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ARROW:
                        Note: Member access
                        proc advance from parser
                        Let member be proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
                        Let member_expr be proc create_node with PHP_MEMBER_EXPR, member
                        proc add_child with member_expr, expr
                        Set expr to member_expr
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
                            Note: Static member access
                            proc advance from parser
                            Set member to proc expect with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
                            Let static_member be proc create_node with PHP_STATIC_MEMBER_EXPR, member
                            proc add_child with static_member, expr
                            Set expr to static_member
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
                                Note: Array index access
                                proc advance from parser
                                Let index be proc parse_expression from parser
                                proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET
                                
                                Let index_expr be proc create_node with PHP_INDEX_EXPR, ""
                                proc add_child with index_expr, expr
                                proc add_child with index_expr, index
                                Set expr to index_expr
                            Otherwise:
                                Set done to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    
    Note: Assignment operators
    If proc match_any with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PLUS_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_MINUS_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STAR_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_SLASH_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT_ASSIGN, PHPLexer.TOKEN_CONCAT_ASSIGN:
        Let op_token be proc previous from parser
        Let op be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with op_token
        
        Let right be proc parse_expression from parser
        
        Let assign be proc create_node with PHP_ASSIGN_EXPR, op
        proc add_child with assign, expr
        proc add_child with assign, right
        Return assign
    End If
    
    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function call parser. The callee is passed in (already parsed by
parse_postfix - might be an identifier, a member access, etc.) and we
parse the (args) part. Empty argument lists are valid; arguments are
comma-separated full expressions. The callee becomes children[0] and
args follow as children[1..N].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes LEFT_PAREN. Creates PHP_CALL_EXPR and appends callee as
first child. If next is NOT RIGHT_PAREN, parses first argument and
appends, then loops on TOKEN_COMMA parsing additional args. Consumes
RIGHT_PAREN. Returns call_expr.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_call" takes parser as Integer, callee as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    
    Let call_expr be proc create_node with PHP_CALL_EXPR, ""
    proc add_child with call_expr, callee
    
    Note: Parse arguments
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        Let arg be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with call_expr, arg
        
        While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance from parser
            Let a be proc parse_expression from parser
            proc add_child with call_expr, a
        End While
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    Return call_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
The base case of the expression-parsing recursion. Recognises every
"atomic" expression form: number/string/boolean/null literals, $vars,
identifiers (function names, constants, class names), `new ...`
expressions, array literals in both legacy `array(...)` and modern
`[...]` syntax, closures `function() { ... }`, arrow functions
`fn() => expr`, and parenthesised sub-expressions. Returning 0 for an
unrecognised token lets the caller (parse_unary or above) decide
whether to report an error or treat the absence as legitimate (e.g.
in `for(;;)` clauses).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequence of token-type tests, each handling its case and returning:
TOKEN_NUMBER -> PHP_NUMBER_LITERAL with value; TOKEN_STRING ->
PHP_STRING_LITERAL; TOKEN_TRUE/FALSE -> PHP_BOOLEAN_LITERAL with
"true"/"false"; TOKEN_NULL -> PHP_NULL_LITERAL with "null";
TOKEN_VARIABLE -> PHP_VARIABLE with name; TOKEN_IDENTIFIER ->
PHP_IDENTIFIER; TOKEN_NEW -> parse_new_expression; TOKEN_ARRAY ->
parse_array_expression; TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET -> parse_short_array;
TOKEN_FUNCTION -> parse_closure; TOKEN_FN -> parse_arrow_function;
TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN -> advance, recursively parse_expression, consume
RIGHT_PAREN, return the inner expression. Falls through to Return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Literals
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER:
        Let token be proc current from parser
        Let value be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with token
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_NUMBER_LITERAL, value
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Set token to proc current from parser
        Set value to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with token
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_STRING_LITERAL, value
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_BOOLEAN_LITERAL, "true"
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_BOOLEAN_LITERAL, "false"
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NULL:
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_NULL_LITERAL, "null"
    End If
    
    Note: Variable
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE:
        Set token to proc current from parser
        Set value to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with token
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_VARIABLE, value
    End If
    
    Note: Identifier (function name, class name, constant)
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set token to proc current from parser
        Set value to proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with token
        proc advance from parser
        Return proc create_node with PHP_IDENTIFIER, value
    End If
    
    Note: New expression
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NEW:
        Return proc parse_new_expression from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Array literal
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ARRAY:
        Return proc parse_array_expression from parser
    End If
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return proc parse_short_array from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Closure
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_closure from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Arrow function
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FN:
        Return proc parse_arrow_function from parser
    End If
    
    Note: Parenthesized expression
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc advance from parser
        Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        Return expr
    End If
    
    Note: Return null for unknown token
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
`new ClassName(args)` constructs an instance. The class name is a
qualified name (can include namespace separators). Constructor
arguments are optional (`new Foo` and `new Foo()` are both valid -
the constructor's parameter list determines which forms are
semantically valid).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes NEW. Parses class_name via parse_qualified_name. Creates
PHP_NEW_EXPR with class_name as value. If next is TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
advances; if NOT RIGHT_PAREN parses first argument, appends, then
loops on COMMA parsing more args. Consumes RIGHT_PAREN. Returns
new_expr.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_new_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_NEW
    
    Let class_name be proc parse_qualified_name from parser
    
    Let new_expr be proc create_node with PHP_NEW_EXPR, class_name
    
    Note: Parse constructor arguments
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc advance from parser
        
        If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Let arg be proc parse_expression from parser
            proc add_child with new_expr, arg
            
            While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc advance from parser
                Let a be proc parse_expression from parser
                proc add_child with new_expr, a
            End While
        End If
        
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    End If
    
    Return new_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Legacy `array(...)` syntax. Accepts a comma-separated list of array
elements (each either `value` or `key => value` per parse_array_element).
Trailing commas are explicitly permitted - PHP has always allowed them
unlike many older languages.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes ARRAY then LEFT_PAREN. Creates PHP_ARRAY_EXPR. If next is
NOT RIGHT_PAREN: parses first element via parse_array_element, appends,
then loops on COMMA: each iteration tests for trailing comma (next is
RIGHT_PAREN) before parsing the next element. Consumes RIGHT_PAREN.
Returns array_expr.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_array_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_ARRAY
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    
    Let array_expr be proc create_node with PHP_ARRAY_EXPR, ""
    
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        Note: Parse array elements
        Let elem be proc parse_array_element from parser
        proc add_child with array_expr, elem
        
        While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance from parser
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                Note: Trailing comma
                Let done be 0
                Set done to 1
            Otherwise:
                Let e be proc parse_array_element from parser
                proc add_child with array_expr, e
            End If
        End While
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    Return array_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Modern `[...]` array syntax (PHP 5.4+). Identical semantics to
parse_array_expression but uses brackets. Both produce PHP_ARRAY_EXPR
nodes so the AST consumer doesn't need to distinguish source syntax.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes LEFT_BRACKET. Creates PHP_ARRAY_EXPR. If next is NOT
RIGHT_BRACKET: parses first element, appends, loops on COMMA with
trailing-comma tolerance (RIGHT_BRACKET ends). Consumes RIGHT_BRACKET.
Returns array_expr.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_short_array" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET
    
    Let array_expr be proc create_node with PHP_ARRAY_EXPR, ""
    
    If proc not_check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET:
        Let elem be proc parse_array_element from parser
        proc add_child with array_expr, elem
        
        While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance from parser
            If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET:
                Note: Trailing comma
                Let done be 0
                Set done to 1
            Otherwise:
                Let e be proc parse_array_element from parser
                proc add_child with array_expr, e
            End If
        End While
    End If
    
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET
    Return array_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single array element: either a bare value (sequential numeric key
auto-assigned) or `key => value` pair. We disambiguate by parsing
the first expression, then peeking for `=>`. Returning a
PHP_BINARY_EXPR with op `=>` for the pair form lets the array
consumer recognise keyed elements uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses first expression. If current is TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW (`=>`):
advances, parses value expression, creates PHP_BINARY_EXPR with
op="=>", appends first as key and value as value, returns the pair.
Otherwise returns the first expression as-is (bare value).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_array_element" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check for key => value syntax
    Let first be proc parse_expression from parser
    
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW:
        proc advance from parser
        Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
        
        Note: Create key-value pair
        Let pair be proc create_node with PHP_BINARY_EXPR, "=>"
        proc add_child with pair, first
        proc add_child with pair, value
        Return pair
    End If
    
    Return first
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP closures (anonymous functions): `function(params) use ($a, $b) {
body }`. The `use` clause is unique to PHP - it explicitly captures
variables from the enclosing scope (PHP does NOT auto-capture like
JavaScript). Arrow functions (parse_arrow_function) auto-capture, so
those don't have a use clause. Capture variables are stored as
metadata "uses" list of names; the body is the only child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes FUNCTION. Creates PHP_CLOSURE_EXPR. Consumes LEFT_PAREN,
parses parameters via parse_parameter_list, sets metadata
"parameters", consumes RIGHT_PAREN. If current is TOKEN_USE: advances,
consumes LEFT_PAREN, reads first variable name, consumes
TOKEN_VARIABLE, appends to uses list; loops on COMMA to collect more
variables. Consumes RIGHT_PAREN, sets metadata "uses". If COLON:
advances and parses return type, sets metadata "return_type". Parses
body via parse_block, appends. Returns closure.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_closure" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION
    
    Let closure be proc create_node with PHP_CLOSURE_EXPR, ""
    
    Note: Parse parameters
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let params be proc parse_parameter_list from parser
    proc set_metadata with closure, "parameters", params
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Note: Parse use clause
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_USE:
        proc advance from parser
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
        
        Let uses be proc list_create from ListCore
        
        Let var_token be proc current from parser
        Let var_name be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with var_token
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
        proc list_append from ListCore with uses, var_name
        
        While proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance from parser
            Let vt be proc current from parser
            Let vn be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with vt
            proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_VARIABLE
            proc list_append from ListCore with uses, vn
        End While
        
        proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        proc set_metadata with closure, "uses", uses
    End If
    
    Note: Parse return type
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance from parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type from parser
        proc set_metadata with closure, "return_type", return_type
    End If
    
    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with closure, body
    
    Return closure
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP 7.4+ arrow functions (`fn(args): RT => expr`) are syntactic sugar for a
single-expression closure that auto-captures every variable it references.
Unlike parse_closure they take no `use` clause and have an expression body
rather than a statement block — we lower body to a single expression node
rather than calling parse_block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_FN, then parenthesised parameter list (parse_parameter_list
attached as "parameters" metadata), optional `: ReturnType` clause
(attached as "return_type" metadata), the mandatory TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW
`=>`, and finally one expression via parse_expression added as the single
child. No body block, no use-clause.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_arrow_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_FN
    
    Let arrow_fn be proc create_node with PHP_ARROW_FUNCTION, ""
    
    Note: Parse parameters
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let params be proc parse_parameter_list from parser
    proc set_metadata with arrow_fn, "parameters", params
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    
    Note: Parse return type
    If proc check with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance from parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type from parser
        proc set_metadata with arrow_fn, "return_type", return_type
    End If
    
    Note: Parse arrow
    proc consume with parser, PHPLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW
    
    Note: Parse body expression
    Let body be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc add_child with arrow_fn, body
    
    Return arrow_fn
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST NODE UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocation site for every AST node so every walker sees identical
shape regardless of construct. Children and metadata get fresh empty
ListCore lists at construction so callers can always append without first
checking for null — this kills a large class of NPE bugs in the parser
recursion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an ASTNode struct literal: caller-supplied node_type and value, plus
two freshly-allocated empty ListCore lists for children and metadata. No
validation of node_type — callers are responsible for passing a defined
PHP_* constant.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be a value of type ASTNode with
        node_type as node_type,
        value as value,
        children as proc list_create from ListCore,
        metadata as proc list_create from ListCore

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Order-preserving append onto the children list. The list maintains
declaration/source order which downstream HIR translation relies on for
e.g. method body statements appearing in original sequence.
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_child" takes node as ASTNode, child as Integer:
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.children, child
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHP nodes need richer attribution than a flat children list can express —
visibility ("public"), modifiers ("static"/"abstract"), return types, etc.
We encode these as `[key, value]` pair lists appended to metadata, giving
each node an associative scratch space without needing a per-kind struct
extension.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh 2-element ListCore list, appends key then value, and
appends that pair list onto node.metadata. Lookup by key requires a linear
scan of metadata pairs — acceptable because per-node metadata count is
small (typically under five entries).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_metadata" takes node as ASTNode, key as Integer, value as Integer:
    Note: Store as key-value pair
    Let pair be proc list_create from ListCore
    proc list_append from ListCore with pair, key
    proc list_append from ListCore with pair, value
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.metadata, pair
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PARSER NAVIGATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
End-of-stream test driven by TOKEN_EOF rather than by position bounds —
the PHP lexer guarantees an EOF sentinel at the end of the token list, so
checking the type of the current token is both safer (no off-by-one) and
matches how all consume/check sites already query.
@End Reasoning

Process called "not_at_end" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc current from parser
    Let token_type be proc php_token_type from PHPLexer with token
    If token_type is equal to PHPLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming type peek: returns 1 iff the parser is not at EOF AND the
current token's type matches the requested type. The EOF guard is critical
because php_token_type on an out-of-range index would dereference invalid
memory.
@End Reasoning

Process called "check" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let token be proc current from parser
        Let current_type be proc php_token_type from PHPLexer with token
        If current_type is equal to token_type:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Logical negation of check, exposed as its own predicate to keep the
recursive-descent call sites readable (e.g. `If proc not_check with ...`
parses better than nesting a `not`). Mirrors check's EOF safety.
@End Reasoning

Process called "not_check" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc check with parser, token_type
    If result is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Up-to-five-way variadic alternative match used by operator-precedence
parsers (e.g. parse_addition picks one of +, -, .). Tested in order; on
the first hit the parser advances and returns 1, otherwise leaves position
untouched and returns 0. Five was chosen because no PHP precedence class
needs more — when one does, callers chain two match_any calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five sequential check/advance/return blocks, each guarded by a check
call so unused slots can be passed as any safe sentinel (callers commonly
duplicate type1 when fewer than five alternatives are needed; the
duplicate hit is harmless because the first match already returned).
@End Implementation

Process called "match_any" takes parser as Integer, type1 as Integer, type2 as Integer, type3 as Integer, type4 as Integer, type5 as Integer returns Integer:
    If proc check with parser, type1:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, type2:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, type3:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, type4:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc check with parser, type5:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Position increment guarded by not_at_end so calling advance past EOF is a
no-op rather than a buffer overrun. This makes recovery code safe even
when an outer caller has already passed the end without realising.
@End Reasoning

Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer:
    If proc not_at_end from parser:
        Set parser.position to parser.position plus 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the token at the current parse cursor without advancing. Wraps
list_get so the position-indexed access remains the single point that
might need optimisation (e.g. cached pointer) later without touching every
call site.
@End Reasoning

Process called "current" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, parser.position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Look-behind by one slot for error messages and disambiguation passes that
need to know what was just consumed (e.g. distinguishing a binary `-`
from a unary one). Assumes position > 0 at the call site — the recursive
descent never calls previous before advance has run at least once.
@End Reasoning

Process called "previous" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let prev_pos be parser.position minus 1
    Return proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, prev_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Soft consume: if the current token matches expected_type, advance past
it; otherwise leave position untouched. No error is raised — the parser
intentionally accepts skipped optional tokens this way (e.g. trailing
semicolons after closing braces in some PHP statements).
@End Reasoning

Process called "consume" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer:
    If proc check with parser, expected_type:
        proc advance from parser
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the lexeme/value of the current token, then consumes it. Used where
the parser needs to capture an identifier or literal text and move past it
atomically — e.g. `$value = expect(TOKEN_IDENTIFIER)` to get a variable
name and the cursor positioned ready for the next decision.
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc current from parser
    Let value be proc php_token_value from PHPLexer with token
    proc consume with parser, expected_type
    Return value
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point matching the naming convention used by sibling
frontends (e.g. `java_parse`, `solidity_parse`). External callers do not
need to know about the internal parse_php_source name; this thin alias
gives a stable surface even if the internal pipeline is refactored.
@End Reasoning

Process called "php_parse" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc parse_php_source from source
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposing the node_type discriminant to HIR translation passes
that cannot see the ASTNode field layout directly. Encapsulation here is
important because the struct order may change for cache locality without
breaking external consumers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "php_ast_node_type" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.node_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the leaf-node lexeme (identifier text, string literal,
numeric literal, etc.). Returns 0 for interior nodes that carry their data
in children/metadata instead.
@End Reasoning

Process called "php_ast_node_value" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor returning the ListCore handle of the node's ordered children.
Callers walk it with list_get/list_length; the handle itself stays owned
by the ASTNode for lifetime purposes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "php_ast_node_children" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.children
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor returning the ListCore handle of the node's [key, value] pair
list. Callers iterate pair-by-pair to find a specific key — see
set_metadata for the storage format.
@End Reasoning

Process called "php_ast_node_metadata" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.metadata
End Process
